@Steve L 

Ah, I did not know that. The Polish spelling has always been Odessa. The millions of Ukrainians living in Poland do not seem to mind it.

As I have written here before, us Polish people love to do weird things to city names: Roma becomes Rzym, Paris Paryż, Istanbul Stambuł, etc. The Polish word for Kyiv is Kijów, and has been for a thousand years, probably.

@Veevee 

You have no idea how tricky it gets in Poland, sometimes. For some reason, for the names of Ukrainian students at our universities we use English transcription, even though a Polish one would work better, and in fact the students often tell us how to write down their names in Polish.

For geographical names though it's different - Poland and Ukraine have a complicated history, as a result of which us Poles have historical, Polish names for most modern Ukrainian cities. Some of those names go back a thousand years, to the medieval Rus states, such as Ruś Kijowska (Kyivan Rus), others are more recent, but still quite old. The Polish Odessa fits into this spectrum, and the Russian-related spelling does not relate to any perception among Polish people of the city being Russian.

